<DOC><DOCNO> AP881120-0026 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-88 1343EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     11-20 0274</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0282</SECOND><HEAD>Afghans Say 3 American Spies Captured; Pakistan Says Plane ShotDown</HEAD><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Afghan government said Sunday ithad captured three U.S. spies, and Pakistan claimed it shot down anAfghan military plane over its territory.   An official Radio Kabul broadcast monitored in Islamabad said anAfghan national was imprisoned along with three American spies. Thestate-run radio did not say where or when these people were captured.   A Western diplomat, speaking on the usual condition he not beidentified, dismissed the Radio Kabul report, saying there are nogovernment officials in Afghanistan.   The aircraft was shot down near the border town of Parachinar, aDefense Ministry spokesman said in a statement to the officialAssociated Press of Pakistan news agency.   Pakistan has repeatedly complained of air violations. The latestreport gave scant details. It said the plane was shot down by``ground fire'' but did not say who was doing the shooting.   Afghanistan and Pakistan signed a U.N. accord in April providingfor the withdrawal of Soviet soldiers from Afghanistan by Feb. 15.The Red Army has been in Afghanistan nine years supporting theAfghan government in its war with guerrillas, who are supported byPakistan and the United States.   Since the accord signing, Pakistan and Afghanistan have beenhurling charges of violations at each other.   Pakistan's foreign minister, Sahabzada Yaqub Khan, saidAfghan-Soviet aircraft have intruded into Pakistan airspace 104times since the accord signing. He made these allegations in aletter sent to the U.N. security council. The news agency publishedthe text of the letter.   The letter alleged the violations left 134 people dead.</TEXT></DOC>